    "# Social Media's Effects on Attention, Mood, and Academic Productivity Among College Students\n",
    "\n",
    "## Permissions\n",
    "\n",
    "Place an `X` in the appropriate bracket below to specify if you would like your group's project to be made available to the public, including the names of the authors.\n",
    "\n",
    "* [X] YES - make available\n",
    "* [  ] NO - keep private\n",
    "\n",
    "## Link to video\n",
    "https://link.to.your.publicly.viewable.video\n",
    "\n",
    "## Abstract\n",
    "\n",
    "Algorithm-driven social media platforms — TikTok, Instagram, Snapchat, Facebook (Reels), and YouTube (Shorts) — have become deeply embedded in the daily routines of college students worldwide. Their AI-powered recommendation systems are engineered to maximize engagement through a continuous stream of personalized, fast-paced content, raising growing concerns about downstream effects on attention, emotional well-being, and academic performance. Despite an expanding body of research linking social media addiction to psychological stress and reduced concentration, few studies have examined these relationships across multiple global regions using comparable measures.\n",
    "\n",
    "This study investigates correlations between daily time spent on these platforms and college students' self-reported attention span, mood state, and academic productivity — and whether outcomes differ between short-form algorithmic platforms (TikTok, Instagram, Snapchat) and feed-based platforms with short-form features (Facebook Reels, YouTube Shorts). We analyzed two complementary Kaggle datasets: the *Students Social Media Addiction and Academic Impact Dataset* (705 observations, 13 variables) and the *Student Social Media & Academic Performance Survey* (405 observations, 21 variables). Key variables include average daily usage hours, self-reported addiction scores (1–10), mental health scores (1–10), GPA, anxiety and depression scales (Likert 1–5), academic distraction scores, and self-esteem measures.\n",
    "\n",
    "We conducted correlation analyses and regression modeling to test whether longer daily usage is associated with lower attention and academic productivity and higher negative mood indicators, and whether the strength of these associations varies across global regions. Our findings revealed strong negative correlations between daily usage and mental health in Dataset 1, with short-form platform users showing significantly worse outcomes than feed-based users across all measures. Dataset 2 corroborated these findings through psychological scale analysis, showing heavier users report higher anxiety, depression, and academic distraction. These results carry implications for how students, educators, and platform designers think about social media's role in academic and psychological outcomes."
   ]
  },
