   "source": [
    "## Research Question"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "51bfd743",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Research Question: What is the correlation between daily time spent on algorithm-driven social media platforms (TikTok, Instagram, Snapchat, Facebook Reels, and YouTube Shorts) and college students' self-reported attention span, mood state, and academic productivity? Do these associations differ between short-form algorithmic platforms (TikTok, Instagram, Snapchat) and feed-based platforms that embed short-form features (Facebook, YouTube)? Additionally, do these correlations vary significantly across different global regions?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0370c4b3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Background and Prior Work"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "881b2d79",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "TikTok, Instagram Reels, and YouTube Shorts are personalized, AI-driven short-entertainment platforms that continuously adjust to user behavior with the goal of maximizing engagement. Their recommendation systems are designed to push highly stimulating, fast-paced videos that keep users scrolling for extended periods of time. Because these platforms are now deeply integrated into the daily lives of many college students, researchers have begun examining whether frequent exposure to this type of algorithmically curated content is linked to shifts in attention, mood, and academic performance.\n",
    "\n",
    "In a mixed-methods study of Generation Z university students in Egypt, El-Shihy found that higher levels of social media addiction were significantly associated with greater psychological stress, reduced concentration, and lower academic engagement. Survey data revealed a positive correlation between addiction scores and students' perceptions of academic interference. In addition, qualitative responses showed consistent themes of procrastination and difficulty maintaining focus while studying. Many participants directly connected their decreased productivity to the amount of time spent on highly engaging social media platforms, suggesting that students themselves recognize a relationship between excessive use and academic disruption.\n",
    "\n",
    "Pan's research on TikTok's personalized recommendation algorithm further highlights the role of algorithmic design. Students described the platform's content feed as extremely relevant and difficult to disengage from, often leading to extended viewing sessions and losing track of time. Participants frequently reported procrastinating more and struggling to sustain attention on demanding tasks after prolonged use. Similarly, Henrich et al. studied adolescents and young adults between ages 13 and 21 and identified associations between long-term exposure to algorithm-driven content and shifts in attention patterns as well as mood regulation. Their findings suggest that repeated engagement with rapid, personalized content may contribute to shorter attentional cycles and heightened emotional responsiveness.\n",
    "\n",
    "Although existing research documents clear associations between social media addiction, algorithmic personalization, attention, and psychological outcomes, much of it focuses on single countries or specific age groups. There is still limited cross-regional research examining whether these relationships differ across global contexts. Our project expands on this work by directly measuring correlations between daily time spent on algorithm-driven short-form platforms and college students' self-reported attention span, mood state, and academic productivity, while also testing whether the strength of these relationships varies across global regions."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0dfcd061",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Hypothesis\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0fb3ff00",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We hypothesize that greater daily time spent on social media platforms will be associated with lower self-reported attention span, reduced academic productivity, and higher negative mood indicators among college students — but that the strength of these associations will differ meaningfully by platform type.\n",
    "\n",
    "Specifically, we predict that users of **short-form, algorithmically curated platforms** — TikTok, Instagram, and Snapchat — will show stronger negative associations with mental health and academic performance than users of **feed-based platforms** such as Facebook and YouTube. Short-form video platforms are engineered around infinite-scroll recommendation engines that optimize for high-engagement, rapid content delivery, making them harder to disengage from and more disruptive to sustained attention. Feed-based platforms, while also algorithmically curated, present a broader and less compulsive content format that includes long-form video, social updates, and news. We include Facebook and YouTube in our analysis because both now embed prominent short-form features (Facebook Reels, YouTube Shorts) that are widely used by college-aged students, making them directly relevant to our research question. Drawing from El-Shihy's finding that addiction scores predict academic disruption, and Pan's documentation of unintended session extension on TikTok, we expect short-form platform users to report significantly higher addiction scores, greater academic interference, and worse mental health outcomes than their feed-based counterparts.\n",
    "\n",
    "We also predict that across all five platforms, greater daily usage will be positively correlated with negative mood indicators such as higher stress, anxiety, and emotional dysregulation, consistent with Henrich et al.'s findings linking sustained algorithm-driven content exposure to changes in mood-related outcomes.\n",
    "\n",
    "Finally, we anticipate that the strength of these relationships will differ across global regions, potentially reflecting cultural differences in technology use, academic expectations, and platform adoption patterns."
   ]
  },
