    "## Ethics"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "123681ed",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "A primary concern is the privacy paradox, where participants may share sensitive personal information without grasping the long-term implications of that data being recorded, such as precise daily routines. Because the question relies on self-reported metrics for \"mood\" and \"attention,\" there is a high risk of social desirability bias. Students may subconsciously underreport their actual screen time on apps like TikTok or overreport their academic productivity to appear more disciplined.\n",
    "\n",
    "The dataset is also susceptible to representation bias and selection bias, particularly regarding the \"digital divide.\" The data we collect inherently excludes students who may not have access to high-speed internet or high-end smartphones capable of running these apps. Social media algorithms themselves reflect algorithmic bias, where certain content or demographics are prioritized over others. If we don't carefully balance our dataset, the conclusions might suggest that \"average\" productivity looks like a specific demographic's experience, further marginalizing students from different socioeconomic or cultural backgrounds. To address this, we will conduct a demographic audit to compare our sample's diversity against global university enrollment statistics and use stratified analysis to look for patterns within specific subgroups rather than just the aggregate \"average student.\" When communicating results, we will explicitly state the limitations of our sample and avoid making universal claims if certain populations are underrepresented.\n",
    "\n",
    "Collecting information related to screen usage patterns, emotional state, and daily behaviors may reveal sensitive details about individuals' lives, even when identifiers are removed. There is also a concern that data collected for a class project could later be misunderstood or used in ways it wasn't originally intended. To reduce this risk, we will only collect information that is truly necessary, avoid gathering identifying details, and make sure data is stored securely. We will also be clear with participants about why their data is being collected and how it will be used and protected. Our analysis will focus on overall trends and subgroup patterns rather than individual-level behavior, and when presenting findings, we will be careful to explain the limits of the data and avoid making broad or judgmental conclusions."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b5c7c112",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Discussion and Conclusion\n",
    "\n",
    "### Why We Revised Our Platform Scope\n",
    "\n",
    "Our original hypothesis focused exclusively on TikTok, Instagram Reels, and YouTube Shorts as the three archetypal algorithm-driven short-form platforms. After initial data exploration, however, we broadened our analysis to include Facebook and Snapchat — and ultimately excluded Twitter/X, WhatsApp, LinkedIn, and several regional platforms (LINE, WeChat, KakaoTalk, VKontakte). This revision was driven by both the data and the real-world media landscape our demographic actually inhabits.\n",
    "\n",
    "Facebook and YouTube were retained because both platforms now embed prominent short-form algorithmic video feeds — Facebook Reels and YouTube Shorts — that are widely used by college-aged students. Excluding them would have under-represented how our demographic actually engages with algorithmic content. Snapchat was retained because its Spotlight feature is a direct TikTok-style infinite-scroll short-form feed with algorithmic curation; the data confirmed this with Snapchat users showing the second-highest academic impact rate (92.3%) and addiction scores comparable to TikTok users. Twitter/X, by contrast, is primarily a text-based feed without short-form video as a core feature, and its users had among the lowest addiction scores and academic impact rates in the dataset — more similar to LinkedIn users than to TikTok users — so it was excluded as out-of-scope. After applying the 5-platform filter, our working Dataset 1 comprises 549 students.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Summary of Key Findings\n",
    "\n",
    "Our analyses across the two cleaned datasets revealed consistent patterns that strongly support the revised hypothesis.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Dataset 1 (n = 549):** Daily usage hours showed strong correlations with every outcome variable: a strong negative correlation with mental health score (r ≈ −0.79, p < 0.001), a strong positive correlation with addiction score (r ≈ 0.83, p < 0.001), a strong negative correlation with sleep hours (r ≈ −0.80, p < 0.001), a strong positive correlation with interpersonal conflicts (r ≈ 0.78, p < 0.001), and a moderate positive correlation with self-reported academic impact (r ≈ 0.61, p < 0.001). Linear regression confirmed that each additional hour of daily usage was associated with approximately a 0.73-point decline on the 10-point mental health scale (R² ≈ 0.62), meaning usage hours alone explain roughly 62% of the variance in self-reported mental health.\n",
    "\n",
    "The platform-type comparison was one of the most striking findings: short-form users (TikTok, Instagram, Snapchat) averaged significantly higher daily usage, higher addiction scores, lower mental health scores, and worse academic impact rates than feed-based users (Facebook, YouTube) — all differences statistically significant at p < 0.001 by Welch's t-test. This supports our central hypothesis that the algorithmic structure of short-form platforms drives stronger negative outcomes.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Regional variation** was modest but present. South Asian and Eastern European/Turkish students tended to report the highest average daily usage hours. While correlation patterns with mental health were similar across regions, smaller regional subsamples limit the strength of these comparisons.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Dataset 2 (n = 296):** The individual-level correlations between parsed daily usage time and Likert-scale outcomes were weaker than in Dataset 1 (r values mostly 0.05–0.12), which we attribute to noise introduced by the free-text time field — entries like \"30 minutes\" were parsed as 30 hours and had to be capped. Despite this limitation, the heavy vs. light user split (split at the daily median) showed consistent directional differences: heavy users reported higher anxiety, higher depression, higher mood modification scores, and greater academic distraction, while light users reported slightly higher self-esteem and GPA. The strongest finding in Dataset 2 was the internal correlation between mood scales and academic distraction — anxiety and mood modification were both significantly correlated with academic distraction (p < 0.05), suggesting that the psychological effects of social media use and its academic disruption are closely intertwined.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Interpretation and Limitations\n",
    "\n",
    "Taken together, these findings are consistent with our hypothesis: heavy use of algorithm-driven platforms — especially short-form ones — is associated with worse mental health, reduced sleep, more interpersonal conflict, and greater academic disruption. However, both datasets are cross-sectional and self-reported, which means we cannot establish causation. It is possible that students who are already experiencing poor mental health or academic struggles turn to social media more, rather than social media being the cause of those outcomes. Future research using longitudinal designs or passive usage tracking would help disentangle these directions.\n",
    "\n",
    "The GPA correlation in Dataset 2 was also notably weak, partly because the GPA distribution is heavily compressed — most students cluster between 3.5 and 4.0, leaving little variance for any variable to predict. This is a known limitation of self-reported GPA in voluntary surveys.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Conclusion\n",
    "\n",
    "Despite these limitations, the convergence of findings across two independent datasets — one measuring behavioral outcomes at scale, one measuring psychological scales — gives us reasonable confidence that algorithm-driven social media use, particularly on short-form platforms, is associated with meaningful negative outcomes for college students' mental health, sleep, and academic experience. The short-form vs. feed-based platform distinction proved to be the most informative axis of comparison in this study, and we recommend that future work continue to treat platform type as a key moderating variable rather than collapsing all social media use into a single measure."
   ]
  },
